Version Control System (VCS)¶

  • a system that records changes to a file or set of files over time so that you can recall specific versions later.

  • VCS allows us to:

    • revert selected files back to a previous state
    • compare changes over time
    • see who last modified something that might be causing a problem
    • see who introduced an issue and when, etc.

  • Using a VCS means that if things go wrong or lose files, you can recover.

    • with git, you get all this for very little overhead.

Local Version Control Systems¶

  • copying files into another directory.
    • error prone, easy to forget which directory youre in and accidentally write to the wrong file or copy over files you dont mean to.

To deal with this issue, programmers long ago developed local VCSs that had a simple database that kept all the changes to files under revision control.

Centralized Version Control Systems (CVCS)¶

  • enables collaboration with other developers.

  • A good example of such a system is Subversion.

    • They tend to have a single server that contains all the versioned files, and a number of clients that check out files from that central place.

    • For many years, this has been the standard for version control.

Advantages over local VCSs:

  • everyone knows to a certain degree what everyone else on the project is doing.
  • administrators have fine-grained control over who can do what

Downsides of Centralised version control:

  • a single point of failure - the server can go down.
  • if the hard disk the central database is on becomes corrupted, and proper backups havent been kept, you lose absolutely everything.

Distributed Version Control Systems (DVCS)¶

  • In a DVCS (e.g., Git), clients dont just check out the latest snapshot of the files; rather, they fully mirror the repository, including its full history.
  • if any server dies, and these systems were collaborating via that server, any of the client repositories can be copied back up to the server to restore it.
  • Every clone is really a full backup of all the data.

  • DVCS systems can have several remote repositories they can work with
  • you can collaborate with different groups of people in different ways simultaneously within the same project.

Brief History of Git¶

  • Linux was created by Linus Torvalds.
  • During the early years of the Linux kernel maintenance (19912002), changes to the software were passed around as patches and archived files.

  • In 2002, the Linux kernel project began using a proprietary DVCS called BitKeeper.

  • In 2005, the relationship Linux kernel Support Community and the commercial company that developed BitKeeper broke down

    • BitKeeper wasn't free to use any more.
    • The Linux development community (especially Linus Torvalds - the creator of Linux) started developing their own tool informed by BitKeeper usage experiences.

  • Git was born in 2005,and has evolved and matured to be easy to use.

    • it is the most widely used version control system today
    • it has an incredible branching system for non-linear development.

What is Git?¶

The main difference between Git and any other VCS (e.g., Subversion) is the way Git thinks about its data. Conceptually, most other systems store information as a list of file-based changes.

Git doesnt store its data this way.

  • Git sees its data like a series of snapshots of a miniature filesystem.
  • every time you commit, or save the state of your project, Git basically takes a picture of what all your files look like at that moment and stores a reference to that snapshot.
  • For efficiency, if files have not changed, Git doesnt store the file again, just a link to the previous identical file it has already stored.

  • Git is more like a mini filesystem with some powerful tools built on top of it.

Most Operations are Local¶

  • Git operations are mostly local to the file system -no information is needed from another computer on your network.

  • most operations seem almost instantaneous since you have the entire history of the project on your local disk.

  • Example -

  • to browse the history of the project, Git doesnt need to go out to the server to get the history and display it for you -it simply reads it directly from your local repo.

  • If you want to see the changes introduced between the current version of a file and the file a month ago, Git can look up the file a month ago and do a local difference calculation, instead of having to either ask a remote server to do it or pull an older version of the file from the remote server to do it locally.

  • there is very little you cant do if youre offline.

Git's Integrity¶

  • Everything in Git is checksummed before it is stored and is then referred to by that checksum.

    • its impossible to change the contents of any file without Git knowing about it.
    • you cant lose information in transit or get file corruption without Git being able to detect it.

  • The mechanism that Git uses for this checksumming is called a SHA-1 hash.

    • it is a 40-character string composed of hexadecimal characters (09, af) and calculated based on the contents of a file or directory structure in Git. A SHA-1 hash looks something like this:

24b9da6552252987aa493b52f8696cd6d3b00373

  • SHA is a hash for each commit

Git generally only adds data¶

  • nearly all actions only add data to the Git database. It is hard to get the system to do anything that is not undoable or to make it erase data in any way.

  • you can lose or mess up changes you havent committed yet, but after you commit a snapshot into Git, it is very difficult to lose it.

Three main states¶

  • The main thing to remember about Git
    • Git has three main states that your files can be in:
      • Modified - you have changed the file but have not committed it yet.
      • Staged - you have marked a modified file in its current version to go into your next commit snapshot.
      • Committed - the data is safely stored in your local repository.

3 main sections of a Git project¶

  • the working tree/directory
  • the staging area
  • the Git directory/repo

Discussion¶

  • The working tree is a single checkout of one version of the project. These files are pulled out of the compressed database in the Git directory and placed on disk for you to use or modify.

    • a project can have many files
    • to checkout means to obtain current version of project files from a repo to disk

  • The staging area is a file, generally contained in your Git directory, that stores information about what will go into your next commit. Its technical name is the index, but the common phrase is staging area.

  • The Git directory or simply repo is where Git stores the metadata and object for your project. This is the most important part of Git, and it is what is copied when you clone a repository from another computer.

Basic Git workflow:

  1. Modify/create files in your working tree.

  2. Stage the changes that you want to be part of your next commit, which adds only those changes to the staging area.

  3. Do a commit - takes the files as they are in the staging area and stores that snapshot permanently to your Git directory.

If a particular version of a file is in the Git directory, its considered committed. If it has been modified and was added to the staging area, it is staged. And if it was changed since it was checked out but has not been staged, it is modified.

Installing Git¶

On Linux

  • On Fedora (or any closely-related RPM(Red-hat Package Manager)-based distribution, such as RHEL or CentOS), you can use dnf:

sudo dnf install git-all

  • on a Debian-based distribution, such as Ubuntu:

sudo apt install git-all

Installing on macOS

  • install the Xcode Command Line Tools.
  • On Mavericks (10.9) or above you can do this simply by trying to run git from the Terminal the very first time.

git --version

If you dont have it installed already do brew install git

  • or a macOS Git installer that is maintained and available for download at the Git website, at https://git-scm.com/download/mac.

Installing on Windows

  • The most official build is available for download on the Git website
  • Go to https://git-scm.com/download/win and the download will start automatically.

Getting started with Git¶

  • useful to customize your Git environment.
  • done only once on any given computer

  • change them at any time by running through the commands again.

  • Git's git config lets you get and set configuration variables that control all aspects of how Git looks and operates.

Your Identity¶

  • set your user name and email address. This is important because every Git commit uses this information, and its immutably baked into the commits you start creating

First - create a local git repository as follows

  1. Create a directory called tutorial
  2. Change to that directory and issue the command git init

What does git init do?

  • creates a branch called master
  • turns your working directory into a local git repository

To uninitilize the repo

  • run rm -rf .git

Checking Your Settings¶

  • check your configuration settings by git config --list command to list all the settings Git can find at that point
  • one can check what Git thinks a specific keys value is by typing git config <key>: e.g. git config user.name

You can set the identity details as follows

  • git config --global user.name JohnK

  • git config --global user.email johnk@gmail.com

What does this do: git config --global --replace-all user.name John_K

  • you need to do this only once if you pass the --global option, because then Git will always use that information for anything you do on that system.

  • you want to override this with a different name or email address for specific projects, you can run the command without the --global option when youre in that project.

Getting Help¶

  • three equivalent ways to get the comprehensive manual page (manpage) help for any of the Git commands:

git help <verb> or git <verb> --help or man git-<verb>

  • Example - get the manpage help for the git config command by running this:

git help config

  • if you dont need the full-blown manpage help, but just need a quick refresher on the available options for a Git command, you can ask for the more concise help output with the -h option, as in:

git add -h

  • by taking a local directory that is currently not under version control, and turning it into a Git repository
  • by cloning an existing Git repository .

Initializing a Repository

  • create a directory in your file system e.g., mkdir my_project
  • change to that directory e.g., cd /home/user/my_project in linux/macos or cd C:/Users/user/my_project

Issue the command git init

Reflections¶

  • a new subdirectory named .git is created
  • it contains all of your necessary repository filesa Git repository skeleton.
  • as of now, nothing in your project is tracked yet.

Suppose that you want to version-control existing files:

  • begin tracking those files and do an initial commit.
  • use git add command that specify the files you want to track, followed by a git commit:

git add *.ipynb

git commit -m "jupyter notebooks"

git push -u origin master

How to clone an existing repository

  • essentially, getting a copy of an existing Git repository
  • Git obtains a full copy of nearly all data that the server has.
  • clone ensures that every version of every file for the history of the project is downloaded by default when you run git clone.
  • if your server disk gets corrupted, you can often use nearly any of the clones on any client to set the server back to the state it was in when it was cloned

The clone command example:

git clone https://github.com/jmathenge/PythonDev

Reflection on clone above¶

  • a directory named PythonDev is created,
  • initializes a .git directory inside it
  • pulls down all the data for that repository, and checks out a working copy of the latest version.

Visit the PythonDev directory that was just created - it has files in there

Recording Changes to the Repository¶

What do you have so far?

  • a git repository on your local machine.
  • a working copy of all of its files.

Next...

  • start making changes and committing snapshots of those changes into your repository

A file can be in tracked or untracked states

  • Tracked files:

    • in the last snapshot, and any newly staged files; they can be unmodified, modified, or staged.
    • tracked files are files that Git knows about.

  • Untracked files:

    • any files in your working directory that were not in your last snapshot and are not in your staging area.
    • after a clone, all of your files will be tracked and unmodified because Git just checked them out and you havent edited anything.

  • when you edit Git sees them as modified, because youve changed them since your last commit.

  • you selectively stage these modified files and then commit all those staged changes, and the cycle repeats.

Check status of your files¶

git status

  • we have a clean working directory - none of the tracked files are modified.
  • Git doesnt see any untracked files, or they would be listed here.

  • we can see that git status tells you which branch youre on and informs you that it has not diverged from the same branch on the server.

  • our branch is always master - the default

    • we look at Git Branching later

Task

Add a new file to your project, e.g. Data.txt. Do it by either:

  • echo "my data">Data.txt or by touch Data.txt or by pasting a new file in your project

Now do git status

  • the Data.txt file is untracked
  • Untracked means that Git sees a file you didnt have in the previous snapshot (commit), and which hasnt yet been staged;
  • Git wont start including it in your commit snapshots until you explicitly tell it to do so. It does this so you dont accidentally begin including generated binary files or other files that you did not mean to include.

Tracking New Files¶

use git add command

git add Data.txt or you can do git add *.txt

Run git status and see it is now tracked and ready for commit

  • A - denotes new files that have been added to the staging area

Viewing Staged and Unstaged Changes¶

  • we can know exactly what you changed, not just which files were changed

    • use git diff command, which answers the questions:
      • What have you changed but not yet staged?
      • And what have you staged that you are about to commit?

  • git diff shows the exact lines added and removed.

For example, after commenting out a statement in DbFirst.py and changing a function, we run git diff:

  • NB - git diff by itself doesnt show all changes made since your last commitonly changes that are still unstaged.

  • If youve staged all of your changes, git diff will give you no output.

Committing Changes¶

Use the git commit -m "some message" to commit your changes.

You can skipp the staging area by `git commit -a -m 'new features'

  • basically, stage and commit in one go

Removing Files¶

  • you have to remove a file from your tracked files (from your staging area) and then commit. - use git rm command

Then git status shows:

  • also removes the file from your working directory so you dont see it as an untracked file the next time around.

Now commit:

Viewing the Commit History¶

  • maybe useful after several commits, or if you have cloned a repository with an existing commit history
  • look back to see what has happened.
    • use git log command.

  • without arguments, git log lists the commits made in that repository in reverse chronological order;

  • each commit is listed with its SHA-1 checksum, the authors name and email, the date written, and the commit message.

  • variety of options to the git log

    • -p or --patch - shows the difference (the patch output) introduced in each commit.

    • one can limit the number of log entries displayed, e.g., -2 to show only the last two entries.

      see out of git log -2

Try git log -p -2

  • it will display the same information but with a diff directly following each entry.
    • useful for code review or to quickly browse what happened during a series of commits that a collaborator has added.

Summarizing options with git log:

  • for abbreviated stats for each commit use the git log --stat

  • we see --stat option

    • prints below each commit entry a list of modified files
    • how many files were changed
    • how many lines in those files were added and removed
    • also puts a summary of the information at the end.

Limiting Log Output¶

  • show only a subset of commits.

  • e.g -2 option displays only the last two commits.

  • -<n>, where n is any integer will show the last n commits.

  • How about time-limiting options such as --since and --until

    • example For example:

git log --since=2.weeks - get the list of commits made in the last two weeks

Undoing Things¶

  • there are some tools for undoing changes.

  • careful - you cant always undo some of these undos.

    • this is one of the few areas in Git where you may lose some work if you do it wrong.

  • a common undo takes place when you commit too early and forget to add some files

  • or you get your commit message wrong.

  • to redo the commit:

    • make the additional changes you forgot
    • stage them

    • then commit again using the --amend

      git commit --amend

Reflections

  • git commint --amend - takes staging area and uses it for the commit.

  • if no changes were made since last commit, then your snapshot will look exactly the same, and all youll change is your commit message.

  • You can edit the message - but it overwrites your previous commit.

Example

Suppose you commit and then realise you forgot to stage the changes in a file you wanted to add to this commit. E.g, in the file DbFirst.py, we add a new function, and then commit before staging. We can solve the issue by:

git commit -m 'Initial commit'

git add DbFirst.py

git commit -m 'div function added' --amend

The second commit replaces the results of the first

Working with remote repositories¶

  • a remote repository is necessary in order to collaborate on a git project
  • we shall discover how to manage remote repositories.

Remote repository - a version of your project hosted on the Internet or network.

  • remote repositories can be read-only or read/write for you.

  • collaborating entails managing a remote repository by:

    • pushing data to it
    • pulling data from it

Checking which remote repositories you have configured

  • do git remote

  • git remote lists shortname of each remote handle youve specified.

  • if youve cloned your repository, you should see origin - the default name git gives to the server you cloned from.

Example

  1. Clone my repository by doing git clone https://github.com/jmathenge/PythonDev
  2. Then do cd PythonDev
  3. Now do git remote
  4. Also do git remote -v
  • the last command shows you the URLs that Git has stored for the shortname to be used when reading and writing to that remote repository

Question: What does git clone command do?

  • it implicitly adds the origin remote for you

We can add a new remote repository explicitly

  • suppose we are in the directory git_tutorial.
  • First, do a clone like this git clone https://github.com/jmathenge/PythonDev

  • do PythonDev and then check git remote -v

    Origin is added implicitly. Let's add it explicitly with a name of our choice:

    • do cd .. and then git init if your directory was not initialised
  • do git remote add p_dev https://github.com/jmathenge/PythonDev

Now do git remote -v and see

We can now use p_dev instead of the whole url.

Example:

  • to fetch all the information someone, e.g. John has but that you dont yet have in your repository, run git fetch p_dev:
    • Johns master branch is now accessible locally as p_dev/master
    • perhaps you merge it into one of your branches
    • or you can check out a local branch at that point if you want to inspect it
      • more on branches later

Fetching & pulling from remote repository¶

  • to get data from your remote projects run:

    git fetch <remote_repository>

What does fetch do?

  • goes to that remote project and pulls all the data from it that you dont have yet.
  • you should then have references to all the branches from that remote, which you can merge in or inspect at any time.

and what happens when you clone repository?

  • git clone automatically adds that remote repository under the name origin.

    • git fetch origin fetches any new work that has been pushed to that server since you cloned (or last fetched from) it.

    • git fetch only downloads the data to your local repository

    • git fetch doesnt automatically merge it with any of your work or modify what youre currently working on. You have to merge manually when ready.

What if you want to fetch and automatically merge?

  • suppose your current branch is set up to track a remote branch
  • use the git pull to automatically fetch and then merge that remote branch into your current branch.
    • its an easier workflow for you
    • by default git clone automatically sets up your local master branch to track the remote master branch on the server you cloned from.
    • git pull generally fetches data from the server you originally cloned from and automatically tries to merge it into the code youre currently working on.

Pushing to a remote repository¶

  • pushing is done in order to share your current work
  • you have to push it upstream.
  • use the command git push <remote> <branch>

Example:

  • suppose you want to push your master branch to your origin server
    • remember cloning sets up those names automatically

git push origin master

Note

  • push works only if you cloned from a server to which you have write access and if nobody has pushed in the meantime.
  • If you and someone else clone at the same time and they push upstream and then you push upstream, your push will be rejected.
  • Youll have to fetch their work first and incorporate it into yours before youll be allowed to push.

more of this when we consider branching

Example of git push

  • on local repository, edit dbpandas.py by adding the line print("New statement")
  • stage the file and commit in one go git commit -a -m 'print statement'
  • you can check git status
  • now push git push origin master Let me now check my remote repository on github

Inspect your remote repository from local

  • use git remote show origin

what the output tells us

  • gives a list of the URLs for the remote repository as well as the tracking branch information.
  • tells us that if youre on the master branch and you run git pull, it will automatically merge the remotes master branch into the local one after it has been fetched.

Renaming remote repository¶

  • git remote rename - used to change a remote repository's shortname. e.g., to rename p_dev to python_dev: 
    `git remote rename p_dev python_dev`

The above rename changes all your remote-tracking branch names too. That is from p_dev/master to python_dev/master.

Removing a remote repository¶

  • to remove a remote repo, do

    git remote remove python_dev Now check with git status:

  • all remote-tracking branches and configuration settings associated with that remote are also deleted.

Before you add and commit your files, you need to understand the stages of a file being tracked by Git.

Committed state

  • A file is in the committed state when all the changes made to the file have been saved in the local repo. Files in the committed stage are files ready to be pushed to the remote repo (on GitHub).

Modified state

  • A file in the modified state has some changes made to it but it's not yet saved. This means that the state of the file has been altered from its previous state in the committed state.

Staged state

  • A file in the staged state means it is ready to be committed. In this state, all necessary changes have been made so the next step is to move the file to the commit state.

    • adds files from working directory to staging area

    • produces a checksum, SHA-1, or the identifier for each file that becomes part of your local repo.
    • produces a snapshot of your history of changes
    • using the SHA-1, we can revert back to previous states of our files

How to revert back to a previous state/commit¶

  • first, we check our commit history using git log
    • commits in my repo look like this

  • There is a commit on Wed Jul 13 at 14:49 that involved removal of data2.txt file

  • Now, I want to revert to the commit before it so I can see the data2.txt file, assuming that I am interested in it again.

    • do git checkout 5a5ae16b5343bb20100aab7066f7c3d0aea383de
    • then do a directory listing, and you will see file data2.txt

  • You can make changes to data2.txt, stage and commit if you wish

  • Revert to the current HEAD using git switch -
